  "output": "This is a pure Python/asyncio job-scraper (no frontend, no React) — I'll map your five categories onto what actually exists: SQLite access patterns, regex/hash recomputation, and resource handling in the async fetchers.\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nFor every job in the batch (potentially thousands per run — Amazon/Microsoft/Google boards alone can yield hundreds to low-thousands), you issue one `SELECT`, then one `INSERT`/`UPDATE`, sequentially:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    else:\n        ...\n```\n\nThat's classic N+1 — N round trips instead of 1. Fix: load all existing hashes in a single query, then batch the writes with `executemany`:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = dict(self.conn.execute(\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs\"))\n\n    new, changed, seen_unchanged = [], [], []\n    to_insert, to_update = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job); to_insert.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); to_update.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        else:\n            seen_unchanged.append((now, job.key))\n\n    if to_insert:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key,...,:now,:now)\"\"\", to_insert)\n    if to_update:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\"\"\", to_update)\n    if seen_unchanged:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", seen_unchanged)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) round trips into O(1) queries + 3 batched `executemany` calls — the biggest win in the codebase given the job volumes in `sources.yaml`.\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-42`\n\n`_compile()` recompiles the same include/exclude regex patterns from scratch on **every job**, inside `match()`, which is called once per job in `filter_jobs`. With ~7 include/exclude keywords and thousands of jobs, that's thousands of redundant `re.compile` calls for identical patterns:\n\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    ...\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled every call\n```\n\nFix — compile once in `filter_jobs` and pass compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = ...\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_re, exclude=exclude_re,\n                                      locations=rules.get(\"locations\"), cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\n(update `match`'s signature/type hints to accept pre-compiled patterns and drop the inner `_compile` calls).\n\n## 3. Redundant computation — `models.py:66-75` (`Job.content_hash`)\n\n`content_hash` is a `@property` that hashes a joined string on every access. In `store.py`'s `diff()`, a changed job gets it computed twice: once for the comparison (`row[\"content_hash\"] != job.content_hash`) and again inside `_update` → `to_row()` → `asdict` + `self.content_hash`. Cheap per-call (short-string SHA-256), but free to avoid — compute once and reuse:\n\n```python\nh = job.content_hash  # compute once\nif existing_hash != h:\n    changed.append(job)\n    row = job.to_row()  # to_row could accept a precomputed hash to skip re-deriving it\n```\n\nLow priority compared to #1/#2, but trivial to fix while you're in that function.\n\n## 4. Sequential pagination latency (not classic N+1, but related)\n\n`fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_amazon`, `fetch_netflix`, `fetch_google`, `fetch_twosigma`, `fetch_optiver` (`fetchers.py`) all paginate with an `await` in a `for` loop — each page waits on the previous one, up to `max_pages` (40 for Microsoft/Amazon). Since none of these APIs expose a total-count you can trust upfront except Workday, true parallelization isn't safe in general (you don't know when to stop). But it's worth flagging as the main wall-clock cost for the biggest boards — a bounded prefetch (e.g., fire the first 3-4 pages concurrently, then fall back to sequential once you've established the \"fresh\" cutoff) would cut latency on Microsoft/Amazon/Google without breaking the \"stop at first empty page\" logic. I'd treat this as optional given the added complexity outweighs the benefit here (this runs on a 12h cron, not in a latency-sensitive request path).\n\n## 5. Memory leaks / resource handling — no issues found\n\n- `fetch_all` (`fetchers.py:767-788`) creates the `httpx.AsyncClient` and closes it in a `finally`, correctly scoped to whether it owns the client.\n- `Store` and SMTP (`notify.py:69`) are used via context managers everywhere they're opened.\n- No unbounded module-level caches or growing globals anywhere in the codebase.\n\n## 6. React re-renders — not applicable\n\nThere's no frontend in this repo (`templates/cv-template.html` is a static Jinja/HTML CV template, not React). Nothing to analyze here.\n\n## Caching opportunities\n\n- **Meta fetcher** (`fetch_meta`, `fetchers.py:537-574`) re-scrapes the careers HTML page every run just to extract `lsd`/`__spin_*` tokens before the GraphQL POST. These tokens are likely valid for longer than one 12h cron interval — you could cache them in the `meta` table (already used for `last_scan`) with a short TTL to skip the HTML fetch on most runs. Marginal win (one extra HTTP call per run), low priority.\n- No other caching gaps stood out — most fetchers are single-shot JSON calls against clean APIs with no rate-limit pressure that would benefit from a cache layer.\n\n**Priority order if you want me to implement:** #1 (store N+1 → batch queries) is the only one with a real, measurable payoff given your job volumes; #2 (regex precompilation) is a quick five-line fix; the rest are minor/optional. Want me to apply #1 and #2?\n",
